WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
Hi everybody, my name is Greg, and I'm one of the designers on staff at Posit, and I'm

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:16.080
the person in the room that's typically keeping an eye on brand design guidelines, like how

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:21.040
things look and how they feel. And here's some brands that I've worked with in the past,

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:27.240
clients that I've had, or places that I've worked. So, as a graphic designer, in a room

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:33.080
full of data scientists, which seems preposterous because I'm your biggest fan, I just want

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:38.439
to say, what do I want? I want design for you to be an afterthought. People in this

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:43.200
room are literally like curing cancer and ending world hunger. You don't need someone

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:48.000
like me in the room saying, cool, cool, cool, cool, cool, cool, but is that the right blue?

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.240
It's just not, it doesn't really fit. And the way to do that is to create a reusable

00:00:53.240 --> 00:01:00.680
custom Quarto HTML theme. Now, Quarto HTML themes are a way that you can customize a

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:09.040
website, coming up manuscripts, books, you can do stuff very quickly, very powerfully

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:14.360
using these themes. Here's one that I kind of put together real quick using Posit's brand.

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:21.480
So let me give you a little bit of background here on how Quarto thinks about HTML themes.

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:26.559
It has a base of Bootstrap 5, and Bootstrap 5 is a very helpful kind of default place

00:01:26.559 --> 00:01:31.360
to start, a good foundation. It's going to decide fonts and colors for you, so you don't

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:34.839
have to, you can just get your data analyses out there. But maybe you work for a company

00:01:34.839 --> 00:01:39.160
that says, you know, we kind of want to use our fonts, we kind of want to use our colors,

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:42.000
or I don't know, maybe you just want to do this for fun, I don't know how you live your

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.720
life. So, here's how you do it. It's very simple. Quarto makes this very simple. You

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:52.160
wire up, you create and wire up a theme.scss file. You can call it whatever you want,

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:57.760
you just put it here and make an SCSS file. So right here, I put it in the Quarto YAML,

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:01.480
which is like the global settings for a Quarto project, but you could also put it in the

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:06.080
front matter of any QMD, or there's a few other places you can put it. So here is a

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:10.479
reveal.js presentation that I've made, that's what I'm showing you now, and I've declared

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:15.720
that the theme is going to be theme.scss, and that's where all of the settings are.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.479
If this project also was going to become a website, you'd do it this way. You'd go HTML,

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:24.759
you'd declare the theme, and I wanted to show you this, you can actually set a light theme

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:29.199
and a dark theme. And just by example under dark, I showed you how you can use many different

00:02:29.199 --> 00:02:34.960
layers of things if you want here. So I've started with default, which is bootstrap 5,

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:38.679
and then I've added on the Cosmos boot swatch theme, but there were a couple things I kind

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:43.839
of wanted to tweak there, so I've also added on my own dark theme.scss. And just with a

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:50.639
comma in between Quarto, we'll understand what you're doing there. All right, so here,

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:54.919
now that you've wired it up, here's the one file you need to make. It's an SCSS file.

00:02:54.919 --> 00:02:57.279
Now there are a lot of different things you can do in this file, I'm just going to talk

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:04.520
about two. The first is SCSS, SAS, and in general, that's going to be one variable that

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:11.000
controls a lot of things, like I want this font to be everywhere. And then also I want

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.279
to talk a little bit about CSS, which in general tends to control just one or a few things,

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:20.800
like when you hover on a red button, I'd like the hover color to be slightly different,

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:25.479
that kind of thing. All right, so here is the SCSS file. Here's how you set it up. In

00:03:25.479 --> 00:03:30.600
the top part, we put this comment, SCSS defaults, and then under that, I'm going to put my SAS

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:33.960
variables, and I'll show you what those are in a second. And then down below here, I've

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:39.880
got the SCSS rules, and that's where I'm going to put some CSS variables. So something

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:43.199
I really want you to pay attention to here is before you put the SAS variables in or

00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:49.399
the CSS, you need to put that comment there for Cordo to pick up what you're putting down.

00:03:49.399 --> 00:03:53.880
Okay, so you need to have at least one of those comments in there for Cordo to understand

00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:59.399
what you're going for here. All right, so what are the variables? Well, Cordo itself,

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:03.800
and all these links will be in a repo at the end, Cordo itself has some very high level,

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:08.800
really powerful SAS variables that are honestly going to get you pretty far. But maybe you

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:14.399
have kind of like a persnickety brand that needs to get a little bit more detail. You

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:18.880
can actually, there's a big bench behind that of bootstrap variables. There's actually like

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:23.720
over 1,400 bootstrap variables that'll let you really fine tune what you're doing. And

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:30.279
the hope is once you've got these changes to these variables in your SCSS theme, you'll

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:33.760
never have to touch them again when you're making this stuff. It's reusable. Now, this

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:38.720
is a RevealJS presentation and that also has, oh wait, one thing I want to tell you.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:43.559
I often don't go to that GitHub repo. I go to Carson Sievert's BSlib package page because

00:04:43.559 --> 00:04:48.320
it lets you filter down and like, I want to see fonts, don't show me everything else.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:51.720
I just want to see fonts, please. I use this all the time. It's really helpful. All right,

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:59.920
so this is a RevealJS presentation and they also have some kind of presentation-y variables

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:03.679
that you can use. And if you're not making a presentation, it's okay that those variables

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:07.239
are in there. It'll ignore them. And if you are making a presentation, Corda will grab

00:05:07.239 --> 00:05:14.600
them. So, it knows what to do with those. All right, so that is my thing. If you grab

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:18.100
those variables, you put them in a theme, the ones that you want to change, you'll be

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:23.519
able to use them for websites, books, manuscripts are in the pre-release, and PowerPoint presentations.

